🔥 Differences (Very Important)
| Feature   | Vector      | List            | Tibble                |
| --------- | ----------- | --------------- | --------------------- |
| Data Type | Same        | Mixed           | Mixed (column-wise)   |
| Structure | 1D          | Flexible        | 2D table              |
| Use       | Simple data | Complex objects | Data analysis         |
| Example   | `c(1,2,3)`  | `list(1,"A")`   | `tibble(x=1:3,y=4:6)` |

🧠 Simple Way to Remember

Vector → Same type (simple)
List   → Mixed type (container)
Tibble → Table (data analysis)


| Feature    | data.frame        | tibble            | matrix    | list            |
| ---------- | ----------------- | ----------------- | --------- | --------------- |
| Structure  | 2D                | 2D                | 2D        | Flexible        |
| Data Types | Mixed (by column) | Mixed (by column) | Same only | Mixed           |
| Use        | General data      | Data analysis     | Math ops  | Complex storage |
| Package    | Base R            | tidyverse         | Base R    | Base R          |


🔥 1️⃣ Data Frame
Definition

A data.frame is a table where:

Rows = observations

Columns = variables

Each column can have different data types

df <- data.frame(
  name = c("A", "B"),
  age = c(20, 25)
)

df <- data.frame(
  name = c("A", "B"),
  age = c(20, 25)
)
🔥 2️⃣ Tibble (Modern Data Frame)
Definition

A tibble is an improved version of data.frame from tidyverse.

Example
library(tibble)

tb <- tibble(
  name = c("A", "B"),
  age = c(20, 25)
)
Key Improvements over data.frame
Feature	data.frame	tibble
Printing	Full output	Clean preview
Strings	Converts to factor (old)	Keeps as character
Column access	Less strict	More strict
🔥 3️⃣ Matrix
Definition

A matrix is a 2D structure where:

All elements must be same data type

Example
m <- matrix(c(1,2,3,4), nrow = 2)
Output
     [,1] [,2]
[1,]    1    3
[2,]    2    4
Key Points

Only one data type allowed

Used for mathematical operations

🔥 4️⃣ List
Definition

A list is a container that can store:

Different data types

Different structures

Example
lst <- list(
  name = "John",
  age = 25,
  scores = c(90, 80)
)
Key Points

Most flexible structure

Can contain anything (even data frames, matrices)

Matrix → Same type
List   → Anything
Data.frame → Table (old)
Tibble → Table (modern)

A matrix stores data of the same type, while a list can store mixed data types and structures.
A data.frame is a tabular structure where each column can have different types,
and a tibble is a modern version of data.frame with better printing and stricter behavior used in tidyverse.

